New util module w/ platform constants (JYTHON, IRONPYTHON, WINDOWS, ...)

Got bored with countless occurrences of conditionals like

    if ((sys.platform.startswith('java') and os.sep != '/') or
            sys.platform == 'cli'):
        # ...

and introduced platform constants to allow using

    if (JYTHON and WINDOWS) or IRONPYTHON:
        # ...

instead. We already had `utils.is_jython`, but decided to use
`utils.JYTHON` style instead. As a result `is_jython` was removed
(#1924).

Assign isExternal JS function to window object

When JS functions are defined with names, they are local variables, and inaccessible
if defined inside a closure. Django-Pipeline concatenates all of our JS into one
big closure. This function explicitly assings the function to a property of the
`window` object, so that it is accessible to other JS functions.

test.helper: shutil.rmtree workaround for Windows

On Windows, shutil.rmtree() raises an exception if it tries to remove a
file marked as read-only.  The files that git creates in the
.git/objects directory are read-only, so the GitRepositoryTestCase hits
this problem when shutil.rmtree() is called during tearDown.  Work
around the issue by passing a an onerror handler to shutil.rmtree()
which detects the case of trying to remove a read-only file, changes the
file to be writeable, and tries again to remove it.

Added --exec_dir option

The --exec_dir option specifies an alternate directory for the
searchgui distribution.  If the option is used and the directory does
not exist, the script will copy the distribution to that directory.
SearchGui updates files relative to the path of the jar file. Thus we
need to copy the jar file, lib, and resources to the working directory
when used in a multiuser environment such as galaxy.
